ownership_description:
Project context (not user work): Flow functionality was evolving to support more advanced scenarios such as DDR and Trigger, which exposed weaknesses in the existing role model. The product needed more flexible role behavior in templates and runtime workspaces so users could preserve role definitions, defer assignment where appropriate, and reuse common assignments more efficiently. :contentReference[oaicite:30]{index=30} PM-defined scope included four major decisions: retain unassigned roles in flow template creation/editing, allow template roles to remain unassigned when creating flows from templates, tune step-start logic when roles appear in assignees, and support a default assignee for template roles. PM also defined important exceptions, such as keeping some role usages mandatory for restricted action types and preserving stricter validation for scheduled flow workspace scenarios. :contentReference[oaicite:32]{index=32}
Technical analysis and design: My T1 work included technical scope analysis, skill/platform assessment, implementation estimation, and defining behavior/interface expectations across platforms and layers. I translated business scenarios into technical rules, exception handling, and engineering-ready definitions. :contentReference[oaicite:33]{index=33}
Implementation: My T2 work focused on web development and detailed implementation design, including role data type updates, workflow role conversion, controller/template default-user loading, store validation, participant form behavior, selector updates, and UI rendering for default assignees and unassigned roles. :contentReference[oaicite:34]{index=34}
Coordination: The work required alignment across web, mobile, BIZ Server, REST API, and iSDK, including shared interpretation of runtime role behavior, API-level behavior, and special-case action support. This included coordinated handling for DocuSign, Time Booking, Jumio, and role-based automation actions. :contentReference[oaicite:36]{index=36}

